y library setups. The context suggests users should research the library and check the documentation. Many DB libraries use Docker images; the Neo4j driver likely should too. I need to choose \\\"no_action\\\" unless I find evidence for extra setup.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Clarifying directives on Neo4j**\\n\\nI need to adhere to guidance that says not to restate deterministic entries. So, I won't mention \\\"neo4j:5.26.12-community.\\\" I could suggest starting a prepared Neo4j server with \\\"NEO4J_AUTH=none\\\" for testing live driver operations. This environment variable isn’t a deterministic entry; it's an environment setup. It’s important to represent dependencies and Docker images accurately. If there’s no testcontainers dependency, the agent uses ProcessBuilder for Docker. Should I include \\\"org.testcontainers:neo4j:1.21.3\\\" since it appears in the upstream POM?\"}]}"}, {"type": "text", "text": "{\n  \"action\": \"advisory_preparation\",\n  \"summary\": \"Neo4j Java Driver can exercise value/mapping APIs locally, but normal documented driver usage runs Cypher through a Bolt connection to a Neo4j DBMS; live Driver/Session/Result coverage needs a Neo4j server.\",\n  \"deterministic_setup\": [\n    {\n      \"kind\": \"docker_image\",\n      \"image\": \"neo4j:5.26.12-community\",\n      \"slug\": \"neo4j\",\n      \"reason\": \"The artifact is the official driver for accessing Neo4j over Bolt, the README example connects to bolt://localhost:7687 and executes a query, and the upstream project uses Neo4j/Testcontainers for integration coverage.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"agent_guidance\": \"For live driver tests, start the prepared Neo4j container with NEO4J_AUTH=none, publish Bolt port 7687 to an available localhost port, wait until the Bolt endpoint accepts connections, then use GraphDatabase.driver(\\\"bolt://127.0.0.1:<port>\\\", AuthTokens.none()). Close Driver/Session objects and remove the container in cleanup. Keep pure value/object-mappi